Life Expectancy Dataset¶

Explaining the Data Set¶

The life expectancy dataset is a collection of data from various countries around the world, providing information on factors that may influence life expectancy. The dataset consists of 22 variables, including the country, year, life expectancy, GDP, population, and schooling. The data spans over the years from 2000 to 2015. The data has been collected from a variety of sources, including the World Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations (UN), and the World Bank (WB). The dataset contains data from 193 countries around the world, making it a comprehensive source of information on global health trends. The dataset is available in CSV format and is easily accessible for analysis. The dataset is used for studying the impact of socioeconomic factors on health outcomes, such as life expectancy. The dataset provides an opportunity to study the relationship between various factors, such as income, education, and health. The dataset also provides insights into the disparities in health outcomes between countries and regions. The dataset has been pre-processed and cleaned to ensure that the data is consistent and accurate.

The world income inequality dataset has multiple tables containing different observations of each countries over the span of around 50 years. dataset "income-share-of-the-top-10-pip" consists of Country, Code, Year, Share of the richest decile in total income or expenditure. dataset "income-shares-by-quintile" consists of Country, Code, Year, Share of each quintile in the total income or expenditure. The dataset has been collected from a source cited in the citations section. The dataset is easily accessible for analysis. It is used for studying the inequalities in countries over the years by comparing their richest and poorest quintiles. The dataset has been already pre-processed and cleaned to ensure that data is consistent and accurate.

Objective¶

The primary objective is to find disparity in life expectancy of among countries based on their status, i.e. they are developed or developing.

Investigating the dependency of life expectancy on various independent parameters like Schooling , GDP etc.

In this Project we analyze the life expectancy data of different countries and explore various factors that affect the life expectancy of countries. In this project various data analysis techniques such as hypothesis testing, time series forecasting, and clustering have been used to gain insights and make informed decisions based on the data.

The project also aims to create interactive visualizations to better communicate the findings and provide a better understanding of the data.

Countries with least Life Expectancy over the years¶

In [15]:
import plotly.graph_objs as go
def get_top6_countries(df, year):
    df_year = df[df['Year'] == year]
    return df_year.nsmallest(6, 'Life expectancy ')

years = df['Year'].unique().tolist()


fig = go.Figure()

df_initial = get_top6_countries(df, years[0])
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=df_initial['Country'], y=df_initial['Life expectancy '], name=str(years[0])))

fig.update_layout(title='Countries with the least Life Expectancy', xaxis_title='Country', yaxis_title='Life Expectancy (years)',
                  xaxis={'type': 'category'}, yaxis_range=[0, 100], barmode='group')

slider = dict(
    active=0,
    pad={"t": 50},
    steps=[],
)


for year in years:
    df_top6 = get_top6_countries(df, year)
    countries = df_top6['Country'].tolist()
    slider['steps'].append(dict(label=str(year), method="update", args=[{"x": [countries], "y": [df_top6['Life expectancy '].tolist()], "visible": [True]},
                                                                          {"title": str(year)}]))
    

fig.update_layout(sliders=[slider])

# Display the figure
fig.show()

Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis 1:

Null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in life expectancy between developed and developing countries.

Alternative hypothesis: There is a significant difference in life expectancy between developed and developing countries.

In [22]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

developed = df[df['Status'] == 'Developed']['Life expectancy ']
developing = df[df['Status'] == 'Developing']['Life expectancy ']

t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(developed, developing)

print('t-statistic:', t_stat)
print('p-value:', p_val)

t-statistic: 29.805188781530223
p-value: 9.034938663789684e-171
In [23]:
# Significance level
alpha = 0.05

if p_val < alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis")
else:
    print("Fail to reject null hypothesis")

Reject null hypothesis

Interpretation: We have conducted a two-sample t-test to compare the life expectancy of developed and developing countries. The t-statistic obtained from the test was 29.805, and the p-value was 9.034e-171. We set the significance level (alpha) at 0.05. Since the p-value (9.034e-171) is less than the significance level (0.05), we reject the null hypothesis.

import plotly.graph_objs as go
import plotly.offline as pyo
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA

df1 = df.copy()

df_dev = df1[df1['Status'] == 'Developed']
df_dev_avg = df_dev.groupby('Year')['Life expectancy '].mean().reset_index()

df_devp = df1[df1['Status'] == 'Developing']
df_devp_avg = df_devp.groupby('Year')['Life expectancy '].mean().reset_index()

model_devp = ARIMA(df_devp_avg['Life expectancy '], order=(1,1,1))
model_devp_fit = model_devp.fit()
forecast_devp = model_devp_fit.forecast(steps=10)

model_dev_fit = model_dev.fit()

Hypothesis 2:
Null Hypothesis: There is no significant relationship between life expectancy and GDP, schooling, and income composition.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a significant relationship between life expectancy and GDP, schooling, and income composition.

In this hypothesis testing we will be using OLS Regression.

Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression is a widely used statistical method for estimating the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. The main principle of OLS is to minimize the sum of the squared differences between the observed dependent variable values and the predicted values obtained from the regression model.

import statsmodels.api as sm
X = df[["GDP", "Schooling", "Income composition of resources"]]
y = df["Life expectancy "]

X = sm.add_constant(X)


model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

print(model.summary())
